The paper proposes a new authentication protocol and discusses its security properties, which are related to cryptography and information theory (cs.CR, cs.IT). The paper also discusses the complexity of the protocol and its implementation on low-cost devices, which are related to computer architecture and computational complexity (cs.CC). Finally, the paper extends the protocol to address active attacks, which is related to machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.LG).
